## Methodology
Methods: 278 participants were recruited following inpatient
admission to a Level 1 Trauma Center after exposure to a
traumatic event. Baseline resting heart rate, cortisol levels,
trauma history, PD and PTSD symptomatology, and de-
mographics were gathered an average of 3.5 days after
trauma, and PTSD symptomatology was assessed again six
months later. Additionally, admission resting heart rate was
collected from the patients’ charts.

## Results
Results: A signiﬁcant correlation was observed between both
admission (r¼.193, p<.01) and baseline (r¼.142, p<.05) heart
rate and endorsement of peritraumatic dissociation. Cortisol
levels were not associated with peritraumatic dissociation or
PTSD symptomatology. Baseline but not admission heart rate
was predictive of PTSD symptom development after controlling
for known covariates, R squared change¼ .014, F change (1,
271) ¼ 4.90, p<.05. Additionally, a history of trauma exposure
was shown to moderate the relationship between admission
resting heart rate and peritraumatic dissociation, ß¼.024, p<.05.

## Clinical Significance
Conclusions: Post-trauma resting heart rate is associated
with the experience of peritraumatic dissociation and is
moderated by a past history of trauma exposure. Further
investigation of the physiological underpinnings of peri-
traumatic dissociation is warranted.
