Background: Obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD) is char-
acterized
by
recurrent, persistent,
intrusive thoughts and
compulsivebehaviors.Ruminative thoughtssimilar toobsessions
and repetitive behaviors similar to compulsions are prominent in
certain neurodegenerative illnesses. Patients with frontotemporal
dementia (FTD) and Huntington’s Disease (HD) can have severe
and early symptoms similar to OCD. These disorders also result in
pronounced degeneration of circuitry thought to be involved in
OCD; frontal cortices in FTD and striatum in HD. We hypothesize
that regional neurodegeneration in these disorders will corre-
spond to subsets of OCD symptoms.
Methods: In this pilot study, we examined the characteristics,
severity, and frequency of OCD-like behavior in 12 patients
with either HD or FTD (6 of each) using the Yale-Brown
Obsessive-Compulsive Scale(Y-BOCS). MR images were ac-
quired on a 3.0T Magnet. Each subject’s T1 weighted
MPRAGE image was used to generate measures of global and
regional brain volume using FreeSurfer software. Brain volume
calculations followed Walhovd et al, 2018 and volumetric re-
gions of interest (ROI) were deﬁned a priori. We looked for
correlations between ROI volumes and severity of obsessive-
compulsive behavior(Y-BOCS) in FTD and HD patients.
Results: In preliminary data, FTD patients have more promi-
nent compulsive behaviors whereas HD patients exhibit more
pronounced obsessive thinking. Structural MRI data suggests
that degeneration in some brain regions may be associated
with OCD severity across disorders.
Conclusions: Our ﬁndings suggest that OCD symptoms may
be correlated with degeneration of speciﬁc brain regions in
neurodegenerative disorders. Continuation of this work could
provide mechanistic and neuroanatomical understanding of
obsessive thinking and compulsive behavior.
